properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Approaching storm will bring significant rainfall Tuesday into Wednesday morning. A developing system will affect Nova Scotia beginning late tonight or early Tuesday. Over northern areas of the province, precipitation will begin tonight as a period of snow and then change to rain early Tuesday morning. Total snowfall accumulations are forecast to be less than 5 centimetres. Over southern areas, rain will begin early Tuesday morning and persist into Tuesday night. Rainfall warnings have been issued for the Atlantic coast, parts of central Nova Scotia, and northern Nova Scotia. It is possible that these may be extended to other parts of eastern Nova Scotia as the system approaches, should the forecast track or intensity of the system change. Rain will change to flurries over western Nova Scotia late Tuesday night as cold westerly winds move into the region and temperatures quickly fall below freezing. Driving conditions may become icy overnight or Wednesday morning as the cold air and flurries push eastward across the province. The travelling public are urged to prepare for potentially difficult driving conditions tonight and Tuesday morning in areas of northern mainland Nova Scotia and northwestern Cape Breton receiving snow. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: The arctic airmass that was over the southern BC interior has retreated northwards with surface temperatures expected to hover slightly above the freezing mark tonight and Tuesday. A frontal system will cross the BC Interior tonight and Tuesday and wet snow is expected. Snowfall accumulations could range between 5 to 15 cm but amounts remain quite uncertain at this time. Wet snow is expected to transition to rain showers later in the day on Tuesday as the airmass warms further. Please refer to your local forecast for further details on snowfall amounts expected for your region. A slight risk of freezing rain still exists tonight for the high elevation travelers routes should temperatures at elevation remain below freezing tonight. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

Wet snow is expected to transition to rain showers later in the day on Tuesday as the airmass warms further. Please refer to your local forecast for further details on snowfall amounts expected for your region. A slight risk of freezing rain still exists tonight for the high elevation travelers routes should temperatures at elevation remain below freezing tonight. ### Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
